{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8da4fb76-7d8d-4ac4-9fe9-96f824d9c8b9","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. From inside the pod:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can copy out and open in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (`--format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools, use the **sidecar approach**: run `dotnet-trace` from a debug container sharing the process namespace (`kubectl debug`).\n- For production-safe collection without installing anything, set `DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics=1` (default) and use `kubectl cp` to retrieve the trace file afterward.\n- Prefer `--format speedscope` if you don't have Visual Studio — Speedscope runs in a browser at [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4eeac0c9-364f-4ffd-a8cd-58bce2396cd9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":334},"id":"e5af4fe7-e8d7-4b90-aaae-6d4471ea0ddd","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:53:28.269Z","parentId":"4654ac05-5037-440b-8cc6-94abce5d1350"}
